 same night as the performances. From 1986 to 1995, ''A Song For Europe'' was also broadcast on [[BBC Radio 2]] with commentary by [[Ray Moore (broadcaster)|Ray Moore]] in 1986\u201387 and later by [[Ken Bruce]] from 1988, although Radio 2 did not broadcast the results show from 1991 onwards.\n\nFrom 1992\u20131994 the programme was again pre-recorded, but the result show was live and broadcast on the same, or following night. In 1997 and 1998, the results were announced the next Saturday after the final and on the following Friday in 1999.\n\nFrom 1957\u20131960, there were various televised semi-finals ahead of the UK final. This was reintroduced in 1996, with a preliminary round of voting to eliminate 4 of the 8 songs. This was televised in 1996 but switched to radio from 1997 to 2003.\n\n===Host(s) and venue===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Selection show\n! Venue\n! National final main host\n! National final co-host\n! Semi final/heat host\n|-\n| 1956\n| colspan=\"5\" {{n/a|UK did not participate}}\n|-\n| [[United Kingdom in the Eurovision Song Contest 1957|1957]]\n| ''Festival Of British Popular Songs''\n| [[Lyric Theatre (Hammersmith)|The King's Theatre Hammersmith]]\n| [[David Jacobs (broadcaster)|David Jacobs]]\n| {{n/a|No co-host}}\n| [[David Jacobs (broadcaster)|David Jacobs]]\n|-\n| 1958\n| colspan=\"5\" {{n/a|UK did not participate}}\n|-\n| [[United Kingdom in the Eurovision Song Contest 1959|1959]]\n| rowspan=\"2\"| ''Eurovision Song Contest British Final''\n| rowspan=\"17\"|[[BBC Television Theatre]]\n| [[Pete Murray (disc jockey)|Pete Murray]]\n| rowspan=\"39\" {{n/a|No co-host}}\n| [[Pete Murray (disc jockey)|Pete Murray]]\n|-\n| [[United Kingdom in the Eurovision Song Contest 1960|1960]]\n| [[David Jacobs (broadcaster)|David Jacobs]]\n| [[David Jacobs (broadcaster)|David Jacobs]]\n|-\n| [[United Kingdom in the Eurovision Song Contest 1961|1961]]\n| rowspan=\"35\"| ''A Song For Europe'' \n| [[Katie Boyle]]\n| rowspan=\"35\" {{n/a|No semi fi