{"title_page": "Bryan Robinson (physician)", "text_new": "{{Other uses|Bryan Robinson (disambiguation){{!}}Bryan Robinson}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n\n'''Bryan Robinson''' (1680\u20131754) was an Irish physician, academic and writer.\n[[File:Bryan Robinson Wilson.jpg|thumb|Bryan Robinson, 1750 engraving by [[Benjamin Wilson (painter)|Benjamin Wilson]]]]\n\n==Life==\nA native of [[Clapham,  North Yorkshire]], Robinson graduated M.B. from [[Cambridge University ]] in 1709, and M.D. in 1711, at [[Trinity College, Dublin]]. He was anatomical lecturer there in 1716\u201317, and in 1745 was appointed [[Regius Professor of Physic (Dublin)|professor of physic]]. On 5 May 1712 he was elected fellow of the [[King and Queen's College of Physicians]] in Ireland, having been candidate on 24 August 1711. He was three times president of the college\u2014in 1718, 1727, and 1739. He was also a member of the Irish Royal College of Surgeons, and a trustee of [[Dr Steevens' Hospital]]. He practised in Dublin, and probably attended [[Esther Vanhomrigh]] ([[Jonathan Swift]]'s \"Vanessa\"), who left him a [[legacy]] of \u00a315. He was on friendly terms with Swift, who recommended him as a doctor to his acquaintances. He was also a close friend of [[Richard Helsham]] and edited his ''Lectures on Natural Philosophy'' for publication after his death.  After years of failing health, which is said to have cused him to become  rather irascible,  he died at Dublin on 26 January 1754.<ref name=\"DNB\">{{cite DNB|wstitle=Robinson, Bryan (1680-1754)|first=Gerald le Grys|last=Norgate|volume=49|page=4}}</ref> \n\nBy his wife Mary he  had  three  sons,   including [[Christopher  Robinson (Irish judge)|Christopher]]  (1712-1787) and Robert (1713-1770).  Robert followed his father into the practice of medicine and like his father was President of the College of Physicians.  Christopher  was  for many years a judge of the [[Court of King's Bench (Ireland)]] <ref>Ball, F. Elrington ''The Judges in Ireland 1221-1921''  London  John Murray 1926</ref>  and is best remembered for having left an impressive  collection  of legal textbooks,  which was purchased by the [[Irish Bar]]  and formed the nucleus of the   present library of  the [[King's Inn]].<ref>Kenny, Colum  \"King's Inn and the Kingdom of Ireland\"  Irish Academic Press Dublin  1992</ref>\n\n==Works==\nRobinson had a reputation in his day, both as a medical and mathematical writer. His earliest work was a translation of [[Philippe de La Hire]]'s ''New Elements of Conick Sections'', 1704. In 1725 he published an account of the inoculation of five children at Dublin. ''The Case of Miss Rolt communicated by an Eye-witness'' was added in an edition printed in London in the same year. This was followed in 1732\u20133 by Robinson's major work, the ''Treatise on the Animal Economy''. It was attacked by [[Thomas Morgan (deist)|Thomas Morgan]] in his ''Mechanical Practice'', and defended by the author in a ''Letter to Dr. Cheyne'' (with the third enlarged edition of 1738). Robinson was a follower of [[Isaac Newton]], and tried to account for animal motions by his principles, and to apply them to the treatment of diseases. He attributed the production of muscular power to the vibration of an ethereal fluid pervading the animal body. His chapter on respiration presaged the discovery of [[oxygen]].<ref name=\"DNB\"/>\n\nRobinson's next work was a ''Dissertation on the Food and Discharges of Human Bodies'', 1747. It was translated into French, and inserted in ''Le Pharmacien Moderne'', 1750. It was followed by ''Observations on the Virtues and Operations of Medicines'' (1752). Robinson also edited [[Richard Helsham]]'s ''Course of Lectures in Natural Philosophy'', 1739 (2nd edit. 1743; reissued in 1767 and 1777).<ref name=\"DNB\"/>\n\nRobinson also wrote a ''Dissertation on the \u00c6ther of Sir Isaac Newton'' (Dublin, 1743; London, 1747); and an ''Essay upon Money and Coins'' (1758), posthumously published by his sons, Christopher and Robert. Part ii. is dedicated to [[Henry Bilson Legge]]. It contains Newton's report to the Treasury on 21 September 1717 on the state of the gold and silver coinage.<ref name=\"DNB\"/>\n\n==References==\n*{{Cite ODNB|title=Robinson, Bryan (1680-1754)|first=G le G|last=Norgate|first2=Jean|last2=Loudon|year=2004|id=23831}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n'''Attribution'''\n\n{{DNB|wstitle=Robinson, Bryan (1680-1754)|first=Gerald le Grys|last=Norgate|volume=49|page=4}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Robinson, Bryan}}\n[[Category:1680 births]]\n[[Category:1754 deaths]]\n[[Category:18th-century Irish medical doctors]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses|Bryan Robinson (disambiguation){{!}}Bryan Robinson}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n\n'''Bryan Robinson''' (1680\u20131754) was an Irish physician, academic and writer.\n[[File:Bryan Robinson Wilson.jpg|thumb|Bryan Robinson, 1750 engraving by [[Benjamin Wilson (painter)|Benjamin Wilson]]]]\n\n==Life==\nA native of [[Clapham,  North Yorkshire]], Robinson graduated M.B. from [[Cambridge University ]] in 1709, and M.D. in 1711, at [[Trinity College, Dublin]]. He was anatomical lecturer there in 1716\u201317, and in 1745 was appointed [[Regius Professor of Physic (Dublin)|professor of physic]]. On 5 May 1712 he was elected fellow of the [[King and Queen's College of Physicians]] in Ireland, having been candidate on 24 August 1711. He was three times president of the college\u2014in 1718, 1727, and 1739. He was also a member of the Irish Royal College of Surgeons, and a trustee of [[Dr Steevens' Hospital]]. He practised in Dublin, and probably attended [[Esther Vanhomrigh]] ([[Jonathan Swift]]'s \"Vanessa\"), who left him a [[legacy]] of \u00a315. He was on friendly terms with Swift, who recommended him as a doctor to his acquaintances. He was also a close friend of [[Richard Helsham]] and edited his ''Lectures on Natural Philosophy'' for publication after his death.  After years of failing health, which is said to have cused him to become irascible,  he died at Dublin on 26 January 1754.<ref name=\"DNB\">{{cite DNB|wstitle=Robinson, Bryan (1680-1754)|first=Gerald le Grys|last=Norgate|volume=49|page=4}}</ref> \n\nBy his wife Mary he  had  three  sons,   including [[Christopher  Robinson (Irish judge)|Christopher]]  (1712-1787) and Robert (1713-1770).  Robert followed his father into the practice of medicine and like his father was President of the College of Physicians.  Christopher  was  for many years a judge of the [[Court of King's Bench (Ireland)]] <ref>Ball, F. Elrington ''The Judges in Ireland 1221-1921''  London  John Murray 1926</ref>  and is best remembered for having left an impressive  collection  of legal textbooks,  which was purchased by the [[Irish Bar]]  and formed the nucleus of the   present library of  the [[King's Inn]].<ref>Kenny, Colum  \"King's Inn and the Kingdom of Ireland\"  Irish Academic Press Dublin  1992</ref>\n\n==Works==\nRobinson had a reputation in his day, both as a medical and mathematical writer. His earliest work was a translation of [[Philippe de La Hire]]'s ''New Elements of Conick Sections'', 1704. In 1725 he published an account of the inoculation of five children at Dublin. ''The Case of Miss Rolt communicated by an Eye-witness'' was added in an edition printed in London in the same year. This was followed in 1732\u20133 by Robinson's major work, the ''Treatise on the Animal Economy''. It was attacked by [[Thomas Morgan (deist)|Thomas Morgan]] in his ''Mechanical Practice'', and defended by the author in a ''Letter to Dr. Cheyne'' (with the third enlarged edition of 1738). Robinson was a follower of [[Isaac Newton]], and tried to account for animal motions by his principles, and to apply them to the treatment of diseases. He attributed the production of muscular power to the vibration of an ethereal fluid pervading the animal body. His chapter on respiration presaged the discovery of [[oxygen]].<ref name=\"DNB\"/>\n\nRobinson's next work was a ''Dissertation on the Food and Discharges of Human Bodies'', 1747. It was translated into French, and inserted in ''Le Pharmacien Moderne'', 1750. It was followed by ''Observations on the Virtues and Operations of Medicines'' (1752). Robinson also edited [[Richard Helsham]]'s ''Course of Lectures in Natural Philosophy'', 1739 (2nd edit. 1743; reissued in 1767 and 1777).<ref name=\"DNB\"/>\n\nRobinson also wrote a ''Dissertation on the \u00c6ther of Sir Isaac Newton'' (Dublin, 1743; London, 1747); and an ''Essay upon Money and Coins'' (1758), posthumously published by his sons, Christopher and Robert. Part ii. is dedicated to [[Henry Bilson Legge]]. It contains Newton's report to the Treasury on 21 September 1717 on the state of the gold and silver coinage.<ref name=\"DNB\"/>\n\n==References==\n*{{Cite ODNB|title=Robinson, Bryan (1680-1754)|first=G le G|last=Norgate|first2=Jean|last2=Loudon|year=2004|id=23831}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n'''Attribution'''\n\n{{DNB|wstitle=Robinson, Bryan (1680-1754)|first=Gerald le Grys|last=Norgate|volume=49|page=4}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Robinson, Bryan}}\n[[Category:1680 births]]\n[[Category:1754 deaths]]\n[[Category:18th-century Irish medical doctors]]\n", "name_user": "Chrisdoyleorwell", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLife", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bryan_Robinson_(physician)"}
{"title_page": "Eldon Hill", "text_new": "{{short description|Hill in United Kingdom}}\n{{for|the hill in Scotland|Eildon Hill}}\n\n{{Infobox mountain\n| name = Eldon Hill\n| photo = Eldon_Hill.jpg\n| photo_caption = Eldon Hill from the bridleway to the north. The start of the quarry workings can be seen on the right.\n| elevation_m = 470\n| elevation_ref = \n| prominence = ''c.'' 70 m\n| listing = None\n| translation = \"Elves Hill\"\n| language = [[Old English language|Old English]]\n| location = [[Derbyshire]], [[England]]\n| range = [[Peak District]], [[White Peak]]\n| grid_ref_UK = SK115811\n| topo = [[Ordnance Survey|OS]] ''Landranger'' 110, 119 [[Ordnance Survey|OS]] ''Explorer'' OL1\n}}\n\n[[Image:Eldon Hill Quarry.jpg|thumb|right|300px|Part of the quarry workings on the north west side of Eldon Hill]]\n[[Image:EldonHole.JPG|thumb|right|300px|Eldon Hole]]\n\n'''Eldon Hill''' is a hill in the [[Peak District]] National Park in the county of [[Derbyshire]], England, {{convert|4|km}} southwest of the village of [[Castleton, Derbyshire|Castleton]]. It is a {{convert|470|m|adj=on}} [[limestone]] hill whose pastureland is used for rough grazing, although a large proportion has been lost to limestone quarrying. It lies within the Castleton [[Site of Special Scientific Interest]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://designatedsites.naturalengland.org.uk/PDFsForWeb/Citation/1002643.pdf |title=Castleton |type=SSSI citation |publisher=Natural England |date=1972 |accessdate=13 February 2018}}</ref> Eldon Hill was formed when a bed of pure limestone was squeezed and upfolded by geological forces to form a dome; it is the highest limestone hill north of the [[River Wye, Derbyshire|River Wye]].<ref name=\"test1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.peakdistrictonline.co.uk/content.php?categoryId=1955 |title=Peak Forest Lead Mines |publisher=Peak District Online |accessdate=13 February 2018 |quote=The summit of the hill at 1540 feet above sea level is the highest limestone hill north of the RIVER WYE.}}</ref>\n\nThe hill is of considerable geological, historical and industrial interest; it lies at the northern limit of the [[carboniferous]] limestone in the Peak District, as further north it merges into the [[Gritstone|millstone grit]] of the [[Dark Peak]]. The name ''Elveden'' is first attested in 1285 as ''Elvedon'' and seems to have meant 'Elves' hill'.<ref>{{cite book |first=Alaric |last=Hall |title=Elves in Anglo-Saxon England: Matters of Belief, Health, Gender and Identity |series=Anglo-Saxon Studies |volume=8 |location=Woodbridge |publisher=Boydell |year=2007 |page=65}}</ref>\n\nQuarrying permission was granted in 1950 and huge quantities of limestone have been excavated, mostly for road-building purposes. A large amount of the northern and northwestern slopes of the hill have disappeared and it has been called the best-known eyesore in the Peak District.<ref name=\"hansard\">{{Cite Hansard |jurisdiction=House of Lords |title=Old mineral planning permissions |url=http://www.parliament.the-stationery-office.co.uk/pa/ld199495/ldhansrd/vo950307/text/50307-05.htm |date=7 March 1995 |column=125 |speaker=[[William Addison, 4th Viscount Addison|Viscount Addison]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930030728/http://www.parliament.the-stationery-office.co.uk/pa/ld199495/ldhansrd/vo950307/text/50307-05.htm |archivedate=30 September 2007 |url-status=dead}}</ref> In 1995 an application by RMC Aggregates to extend the quarrying further east was denied as parliament tightened up on environmental problems caused by old mineral permissions granted between 1948 and 1981. The quarry closed in 1999 and now stands unused with vegetation starting to grow on the quarry face. There have been some attempts at natural restoration with several aquatic pools being established in the former workings.<ref name=\"test4\">{{cite web |url=http://www.peakdistrict.gov.uk/bap-report2002.pdf |title=Peak District Biodiversity Action Plan Annual Report No. 1 |date=October 2002 |archivedate=20 July 2011|archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20110720111424/http://www.peakdistrict.gov.uk/bap-report2002.pdf  |publisher=Peak District National Park |accessdate=13 February 2018 |quote=Several pools have been established at Eldon Hill quarry as part of the restoration scheme (RMC).}}</ref> The termination of quarrying has also given [[Caving|cavers]] the chance to explore some of the narrow caves exposed by the work, with Sidetrack Cave (discovered 2002)<ref>{{cite book |title=Caves of the Peak District |publisher=Derbyshire Caving Association |date=2010 |first1=Iain |last1=Barker |first2=John S. |last2=Beck |isbn=9780956347329 |page=127}}</ref> being one of the most impressive.\n\n350 metres south of the summit lies Eldon Hole. At 55 metres it is the deepest pothole in the area and was named as one of the [[Seven Wonders of the Peak]] by the philosopher [[Thomas Hobbes]] in 1636.<ref name=\"test5\">{{cite web |url=http://www.peakdistrictview.com/?page=wonders |title=Wonders of the Peak |publisher=Peak District View |accessdate=13 February 2018}}</ref> According to folk tradition, it is the abode of the Devil.<ref>{{cite web |title=Eldon Hole |url=http://www.cheshirenow.co.uk/eldon_hole.html |publisher=Cheshirenow.co.uk |accessdate=13 February 2018}}</ref> Close to the summit of the hill lies a [[Bronze Age]] [[tumulus]], a large burial site measuring 16 by 15 metres and 1.5 metres high. The tumulus, a Scheduled Monument,<ref name=\"NHLE\">{{National Heritage List for England| num=1008063 |desc=Eldon Hill bowl barrow |grade= |accessdate=13 February 2018}}</ref> has been excavated on several occasions with human skeletons and jewellery amongst the finds.<ref name=\"test6\">{{cite web |url=http://www.peakdistrictview.com/?page=place&placeid=85 |title=Eldon Hill Barrow |publisher=Peak District View |accessdate=13 February 2018}}</ref> The hill is dotted with numerous [[lead]] mines, all disused and many capped off for safety.\n\nEldon Hill can be climbed either from the villages of [[Peak Forest]] to the south or Castleton to the north. The approach from Castleton goes up [[Cave Dale]] with a return down [[Winnats Pass]] to give a very interesting walk. The approach from Peak Forest is shorter and passes Eldon Hole on the way. The summit of the hill stands just 100 metres from the edge of the fenced quarry workings and gives good views with [[Mam Tor]], [[Axe Edge Moor]] and the town of [[Buxton]] all well seen.\n\n== References ==\n* [http://www.english-nature.org.uk/citation/citation_photo/1002643.pdf Castleton SSSI at English Heritage]  \n* [http://www.cressbrook.co.uk/visits/eldonhole.php Eldon Hole info from www.cressbrook.co.uk]\n* [http://freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.com/~hadfield/acornerof.htm Info from a Corner of the Derbyshire Peak]\n* [https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld199495/ldhansrd/vo950307/text/50307-05.htm Hansard on Quarry]\n\n'''Footnotes'''\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{coord|53.32670|N|1.82880|W|region:GB_source:enwiki-osgb36(SK115811)|display=title}}<!-- Note: WGS84 lat/long, converted from OSGB36 grid ref -->\n\n{{Peaks of the Peak District}}\n\n[[Category:Mountains and hills of the Peak District]]\n[[Category:Mountains and hills of Derbyshire]]\n[[Category:Tumuli in England]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Hill in United Kingdom}}\n{{for|the hill in Scotland|Eildon Hill}}\n\n{{Infobox mountain\n| name = Eldon Hill\n| photo = Eldon_Hill.jpg\n| photo_caption = Eldon Hill from the bridleway to the north. The start of the quarry workings can be seen on the right.\n| elevation_m = 470\n| elevation_ref = \n| prominence = ''c.'' 70 m\n| listing = None\n| translation = \"Elves Hill\"\n| language = [[Old English language|Old English]]\n| location = [[Derbyshire]], [[England]]\n| range = [[Peak District]], [[White Peak]]\n| grid_ref_UK = SK115811\n| topo = [[Ordnance Survey|OS]] ''Landranger'' 110, 119 [[Ordnance Survey|OS]] ''Explorer'' OL1\n}}\n\n[[Image:Eldon Hill Quarry.jpg|thumb|right|300px|Part of the quarry workings on the north west side of Eldon Hill]]\n[[Image:EldonHole.JPG|thumb|right|300px|Eldon Hole]]\n\n'''Eldon Hill''' is a hill in the [[Peak District]] National Park in the county of [[Derbyshire]], England, {{convert|4|km}} southwest of the village of [[Castleton, Derbyshire|Castleton]]. It is a {{convert|470|m|adj=on}} [[limestone]] hill whose pastureland is used for rough grazing, although a large proportion has been lost to limestone quarrying. It lies within the Castleton [[Site of Special Scientific Interest]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://designatedsites.naturalengland.org.uk/PDFsForWeb/Citation/1002643.pdf |title=Castleton |type=SSSI citation |publisher=Natural England |date=1972 |accessdate=13 February 2018}}</ref> Eldon Hill was formed when a bed of pure limestone was squeezed and upfolded by geological forces to form a dome; it is the highest limestone hill north of the [[River Wye, Derbyshire|River Wye]].<ref name=\"test1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.peakdistrictonline.co.uk/content.php?categoryId=1955 |title=Peak Forest Lead Mines |publisher=Peak District Online |accessdate=13 February 2018 |quote=The summit of the hill at 1540 feet above sea level is the highest limestone hill north of the RIVER WYE.}}</ref>\n\nThe hill is of considerable geological, historical and industrial interest; it lies at the northern limit of the [[carboniferous]] limestone in the Peak District, as further north it merges into the [[Gritstone|millstone grit]] of the [[Dark Peak]]. The name ''Elveden'' is first attested in 1285 as ''Elvedon'' and seems to have meant 'Elves' hill'.<ref>{{cite book |first=Alaric |last=Hall |title=Elves in Anglo-Saxon England: Matters of Belief, Health, Gender and Identity |series=Anglo-Saxon Studies |volume=8 |location=Woodbridge |publisher=Boydell |year=2007 |page=65}}</ref>\n\nQuarrying permission was granted in 1950 and huge quantities of limestone have been excavated, mostly for road-building purposes. A large amount of the northern and northwestern slopes of the hill have disappeared and it has been called the best-known eyesore in the Peak District.<ref name=\"hansard\">{{Cite Hansard |jurisdiction=House of Lords |title=Old mineral planning permissions |url=http://www.parliament.the-stationery-office.co.uk/pa/ld199495/ldhansrd/vo950307/text/50307-05.htm |date=7 March 1995 |column=125 |speaker=[[William Addison, 4th Viscount Addison|Viscount Addison]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930030728/http://www.parliament.the-stationery-office.co.uk/pa/ld199495/ldhansrd/vo950307/text/50307-05.htm |archivedate=30 September 2007 |url-status=dead}}</ref> In 1995 an application by RMC Aggregates to extend the quarrying further east was denied as parliament tightened up on environmental problems caused by old mineral permissions granted between 1948 and 1981. The quarry closed in 1999 and now stands unused with vegetation starting to grow on the quarry face. There have been some attempts at natural restoration with several aquatic pools being established in the former workings.<ref name=\"test4\">{{cite web |url=http://www.peakdistrict.gov.uk/bap-report2002.pdf |title=Peak District Biodiversity Action Plan Annual Report No. 1 |date=October 2002 |archivedate=20 July 2011|archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20110720111424/http://www.peakdistrict.gov.uk/bap-report2002.pdf  |publisher=Peak District National Park |accessdate=13 February 2018 |quote=Several pools have been established at Eldon Hill quarry as part of the restoration scheme (RMC).}}</ref> The termination of quarrying has also given [[Caving|cavers]] the chance to explore some of the narrow caves exposed by the work, with Sidetrack Cave (discovered 2002)<ref>{{cite book |title=Caves of the Peak District |publisher=Derbyshire Caving Association |date=2010 |first1=Iain |last1=Barker |first2=John S. |last2=Beck |isbn=9780956347329 |page=127}}</ref> being one of the most impressive.\n\n350 metres south of the summit lies Eldon Hole. At 55 metres it is the deepest pothole in the area and was named as one of the Seven Wonders of the Peak by the philosopher [[Thomas Hobbes]] in 1636.<ref name=\"test5\">{{cite web |url=http://www.peakdistrictview.com/?page=wonders |title=Wonders of the Peak |publisher=Peak District View |accessdate=13 February 2018}}</ref> According to folk tradition, it is the abode of the Devil.<ref>{{cite web |title=Eldon Hole |url=http://www.cheshirenow.co.uk/eldon_hole.html |publisher=Cheshirenow.co.uk |accessdate=13 February 2018}}</ref> Close to the summit of the hill lies a [[Bronze Age]] [[tumulus]], a large burial site measuring 16 by 15 metres and 1.5 metres high. The tumulus, a Scheduled Monument,<ref name=\"NHLE\">{{National Heritage List for England| num=1008063 |desc=Eldon Hill bowl barrow |grade= |accessdate=13 February 2018}}</ref> has been excavated on several occasions with human skeletons and jewellery amongst the finds.<ref name=\"test6\">{{cite web |url=http://www.peakdistrictview.com/?page=place&placeid=85 |title=Eldon Hill Barrow |publisher=Peak District View |accessdate=13 February 2018}}</ref> The hill is dotted with numerous [[lead]] mines, all disused and many capped off for safety.\n\nEldon Hill can be climbed either from the villages of [[Peak Forest]] to the south or Castleton to the north. The approach from Castleton goes up [[Cave Dale]] with a return down [[Winnats Pass]] to give a very interesting walk. The approach from Peak Forest is shorter and passes Eldon Hole on the way. The summit of the hill stands just 100 metres from the edge of the fenced quarry workings and gives good views with [[Mam Tor]], [[Axe Edge Moor]] and the town of [[Buxton]] all well seen.\n\n== References ==\n* [http://www.english-nature.org.uk/citation/citation_photo/1002643.pdf Castleton SSSI at English Heritage]  \n* [http://www.cressbrook.co.uk/visits/eldonhole.php Eldon Hole info from www.cressbrook.co.uk]\n* [http://freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.com/~hadfield/acornerof.htm Info from a Corner of the Derbyshire Peak]\n* [https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld199495/ldhansrd/vo950307/text/50307-05.htm Hansard on Quarry]\n\n'''Footnotes'''\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{coord|53.32670|N|1.82880|W|region:GB_source:enwiki-osgb36(SK115811)|display=title}}<!-- Note: WGS84 lat/long, converted from OSGB36 grid ref -->\n\n{{Peaks of the Peak District}}\n\n[[Category:Mountains and hills of the Peak District]]\n[[Category:Mountains and hills of Derbyshire]]\n[[Category:Tumuli in England]]\n", "name_user": "Douglal", "label": "safe", "comment": "Link to Seven Wonders of the Peak", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eldon_Hill"}
{"title_page": "Johnny Bach", "text_new": "{{about|the basketball player and coach|the Welsh actor|John Bach}}\n{{Infobox basketball biography\n| name         = Johnny Bach\n| image        = \n| width        =\n| caption      =\n| position     = [[Small forward]] / [[Guard (basketball)|Guard]]\n| height_ft    = 6\n| height_in    = 2\n| weight_lb    = 180\n| number       = 17\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date|1924|7|10}}\n| birth_place  = [[Brooklyn, New York]]\n| death_date   = {{death date and age|2016|1|18|1924|7|10}}\n| death_place  = [[Chicago|Chicago, Illinois]]\n| nationality  = American\n| high_school  = [[St. John's Preparatory School (New York City)|St. John's Preparatory]]<br/>(New York City, New York)\n| college      = [[Fordham Rams men's basketball|Fordham]] (1943\u20131947)\n| draft_year   = 1948\n| draft_league = BAA\n| draft_round  = --\n| draft_pick   = --\n| draft_team   = [[Boston Celtics]]\n| career_start = 1948\n| career_end   = 1950\n| coach_start  = 1950\n| coach_end    = 2006\n| years1          = [[1948\u201349 BAA season|1948\u20131949]]\n| team1           = [[Boston Celtics]]\n| years2          = 1949\u20131950\n| team2           = [[Hartford Hurricanes]]\n| cyears1         = 1950\u20131968\n| cteam1          = [[Fordham Rams men's basketball|Fordham]]\n| cyears2         = 1968\u20131978\n| cteam2          = [[Penn State Nittany Lions men's basketball|Penn State]]\n| cyears3         = {{nbay|1979|start}}\u2013{{nbay|1982|end}}\n| cteam3          = [[Golden State Warriors]] (assistant)\n| cyears4         = {{nbay|1979|end}},<br/>{{nbay|1983|start}}\u2013{{nbay|1985|end}}\n| cteam4          = Golden State Warriors\n| cyears5         = {{nbay|1986|start}}\u2013{{nbay|1993|end}}\n| cteam5          = [[Chicago Bulls]] (assistant)\n| cyears6         = {{nbay|1994|start}}\u2013{{nbay|1995|end}}\n| cteam6          = [[Charlotte Hornets]] (assistant)\n| cyears7         = {{nbay|1996|start}}\u2013{{nbay|1997|end}}\n| cteam7          = [[Detroit Pistons]] (assistant)\n| cyears8         = {{nbay|2001|start}}\u2013{{nbay|2002|end}}\n| cteam8          = [[Washington Wizards]] (assistant)\n| cyears9         = {{nbay|2003|start}}\u2013{{nbay|2005|end}}\n| cteam9          = Chicago Bulls (assistant)\n| stats_league  = BAA\n| stat1label    = [[Point (basketball)|Points]]\n| stat1value    = 119 (3.5 ppg)\n| stat2label    = [[Assist (basketball)|Assists]]\n| stat2value    = 25 (0.7 apg)\n| stat3label    = [[Games played]]\n| stat3value    = 34\n| bbr           = bachjo01\n}}\n'''John William Bach''' (July 10, 1924 \u2013 January 18, 2016) was an American professional [[basketball]] player and coach.  A [[forward (basketball)|forward]]/[[guard (basketball)|guard]], Bach played [[college basketball]] at [[Fordham University]] and [[Brown University]].  He was selected by the [[Boston Celtics]] in the 1948 [[National Basketball Association|Basketball Association of America]] (BAA) Draft, and played 34 games for the Celtics.\n\n==Career==\nIn 1950, at age 26, Bach became one of the nation's youngest head coaches at a major college when he took over the coaching job at [[Fordham University|Fordham]].{{citation needed|date=March 2018}} He spent 18 years there, taking seven Ram teams to post-season tourneys, before starting a long and successful coaching career at [[Penn State]], where he joined three old friends from Brown; [[Rip Engle]], [[Joe Paterno]] and [[Joe McMullen]]. Bach would later coach the [[Golden State Warriors]] for three years.  He served as an interim coach in 1980, and then as the full-time coach from 1983 to 1986. In 1986 Bach joined the [[Chicago Bulls]] as an assistant. After the team won three championships from 1991 to 1993, Bach moved on to coaching jobs with the [[Charlotte Hornets (1988\u20132002)|Charlotte Hornets]], [[Detroit Pistons]] and [[Washington Wizards]]. He returned to the Bulls in 2003, and retired in 2006.<ref name=paint>Shamus Tooney. \"From courtside to art gallery \u2013 Bulls' Bach shows off watercolors\". ''Chicago Sun-Times''. September 20, 2007. 12.</ref>\n\n==Later life==\nAfter retiring from basketball, Bach turned to painting. In 2007, thirty-two of his watercolors were put on display at the Sevan Gallery in [[Skokie, Illinois]].<ref name=paint/>\n\n==Death==\nBach died on January 18, 2016 in [[Chicago]] at the age of 91.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/basketball/bulls/ct-johnny-bach-bulls-20160118-story.html|title=Former Bulls assistant coach Johnny Bach dies|work=Chicago Tribune|accessdate=January 18, 2016|date=January 18, 2016|author=K. C. Johnson}}</ref> Bach's funeral was held two days later on January 20, 2016 at the [[Old St. Patrick's Church (Chicago)|Old St. Patrick's Church]] in Chicago.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/basketball/bulls/ct-bulls-bach-funeral-20160120-story.html |title=Bulls greats pay their respects at Johnny Bach's funeral |newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]] |date=January 20, 2016 |accessdate=January 29, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==BAA career statistics==\n{| class=\"toccolours\" style=\"font-size: 90%; white-space: nowrap;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"6\" style=\"background:#f2f2f2; border:1px solid #aaa;\"| Legend\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f2f2f2; border:1px solid black;\"| &nbsp;&nbsp;GP\n| Games played\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f2f2f2; border:1px solid black;\"| &nbsp;FG%&nbsp;\n| style=\"padding-right: 8px\" | [[Field goal (basketball)|Field-goal]] percentage\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f2f2f2; border:1px solid black;\"| &nbsp;FT%&nbsp;\n| [[Free throw|Free-throw]] percentage\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f2f2f2; border:1px solid black;\"| &nbsp;APG&nbsp;\n| [[Assist (basketball)|Assists]] per game\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f2f2f2; border:1px solid black;\"| &nbsp;PPG&nbsp;\n| Points per game\n|-\n|}\n\n===Regular season===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size:95%; text-align:right;\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Team\n! GP\n! FG%\n! FT%\n! APG\n! PPG\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"| [